Sentiment Analysis on Philosophical Texts¶

by: Weijie Xia(wx2281)

In this project, the analysis will be based on the dataset for the philosophy data project. As time goes by, we notice a trend that the sentiment of the philosophical text tend to go from positive to neutral or even negative. This analysis aim to offer a perspective to understand this observation.

Next, we will add in sentiment score based on the philosophical texts in the dataset. This is achieved by using the SentimentIntensityAnalyzer from nltk package. The compound sentiment score will range from -1 to 1, indicating respectively from a negative attitude to a positive attitude.

In [18]:
# sentiment analysis
sia = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
df['sentiment_scores'] = df['sentence_str'].apply(lambda x: sia.polarity_scores(x))
df['compound_sent_score'] = df['sentiment_scores'].apply(lambda x: x['compound'])

Delete unnecessary columns for this analysis and save the preprocessed dataset.

In [20]:
df.drop(columns=['sentence_spacy','corpus_edition_date','sentiment_scores', 'lemmatized_str', 'sentence_lowered'], inplace=True)

3. Overall Word Frequency Analysis¶

We will take a look at the word choices among these texts. We may notice that "one" and "things" appear most frequently in the texts, it may imply that the relationship between a person and the world around him/her would be the most discussed topic.

In [8]:
# text analysis 


#Flatten the list of tokens into a single list
# ast.literal_eval convert a list in the form of string into a actual list
df['tokenized_txt'] = df['tokenized_txt'].apply(lambda x: ast.literal_eval(x))

all_tokens = [token for tokens in df['tokenized_txt'] for token in tokens]

# Remove stop words from the tokenized text
stop_words = set(stopwords.words("english"))
all_tokens = [token for token in all_tokens if token.lower() not in stop_words]

# Plot the word frequency distribution
fd = FreqDist(all_tokens)
plt.figure(figsize=(16,6))
fd.plot(30, cumulative=False, title='Word Frequency Distribution')


# print unique words
num_unique_words = len(set(all_tokens))
print(f"Number of unique words: {num_unique_words}")

4.3 Sentiment shift across time based on school of thoughts¶

In order to get a clearer view of what school of thoughts cause the change in the sentiment, we focus on the school of thoughts after 1500. we may notice that, compared to rationalism and empiricism, feminism(especially after 1950), analytic and continental exhibit the lowest sentiment compound scores on average among all the school of thoughts.

plt.show()

5. Analysis on the Shift of the Sentiment¶

In this section, we want to take a close look on the five school of thoughts mentioned last section, which is rationalism, empiricism, feminism(especially after 1950), analytic and continental. We will perform word frequency analysis on each of the school and train Word2vec models on each of them to see different schools of thoughts react to same words. Through the analysis on texts we wish to know what cause the sentiment shift.

5.1 Word clouds analysis for different schools of thoughts¶

In [28]:
# Filter different dataframe for different schools

df_rationalism = df[df['school'] == 'rationalism']
df_empiricism = df[df['school'] == 'empiricism']


df_analytic = df[df['school'] == 'analytic']
df_continental = df[df['school'] == 'continental']
df_feminism = df[(df['school'] == 'feminism') & (df['original_publication_date'] >= 1950)]
In [40]:
# Define a function that take in the Dataframe we filtered above
# and output a string of words that can be used to generate word cloud

def get_wordcloud_text(dataframe):
    stop_words = set(stopwords.words("english"))
    tokens_list = [token for tokens in dataframe['tokenized_txt'] for token in tokens]
    # Remove stop words from the tokenized text
    tokens_list = [token for token in tokens_list if token.lower() not in stop_words]
    return ' '.join(tokens_list)

rationalism_text = get_wordcloud_text(df_rationalism)
analytic_text = get_wordcloud_text(df_analytic)
continental_text = get_wordcloud_text(df_continental)
feminism_text = get_wordcloud_text(df_feminism)
empiricism_text = get_wordcloud_text(df_empiricism)



# Create word clouds for each school
wordcloud_rationalism = WordCloud().generate(rationalism_text)
wordcloud_analytic = WordCloud().generate(analytic_text)
wordcloud_continental = WordCloud().generate(continental_text)
wordcloud_feminism = WordCloud().generate(feminism_text)
wordcloud_empiricism = WordCloud().generate(empiricism_text)

# Plot subplots
fig, axs = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(15, 15))
axs[0, 0].imshow(wordcloud_rationalism, cmap='gray')
axs[0, 0].set_title('Rationalism')
axs[0, 1].imshow(wordcloud_empiricism, cmap='gray')
axs[0, 1].set_title('Empiricism')
axs[1, 0].imshow(wordcloud_continental, cmap='gray')
axs[1, 0].set_title('Continental')
axs[1, 1].imshow(wordcloud_feminism, cmap='gray')
axs[1, 1].set_title('Feminism')
axs[2, 0].imshow(wordcloud_analytic, cmap='gray')
axs[2, 0].set_title('Analytic')

# Adjust subplot spacing
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.5)

# Show plot
plt.show()

From the word clouds of Rationalism and Empiricism, the frequent words used in the texts are positive or neutral. We can see words such as "nature", "idea", "mind", "soul" and "reason." However, after 20 centuries, the philosophers in Analytic, Continental and Feminism based their discussions on more radical subjects such as "slavery", "racism" , "problem", and "madness." These are powerful words that tend to result in negative sentiment. Therefore, it results in a negative shift in sentiment of the texts as time goes by.

5.2 Word2Vec models for different schools of thoughts¶

Word2vec is powerful tool from the gensim package that is for topic modelling. Word2vec model can vectorize the texts and allow us to find the most similar words.

Train the models first.

In [41]:
# train word2vec models for different schools of thoughts

w2v_model_rationalism = Word2Vec(df_rationalism['tokenized_txt'], min_count=1)
w2v_model_empiricism = Word2Vec(df_empiricism['tokenized_txt'], min_count=1)


w2v_model_analytic = Word2Vec(df_analytic['tokenized_txt'], min_count=1)
w2v_model_feminism = Word2Vec(df_feminism['tokenized_txt'], min_count=1)
w2v_model_continental = Word2Vec(df_continental['tokenized_txt'], min_count=1)

# test it out

# happiness for rationalism
sims = w2v_model_rationalism.wv.most_similar('happiness', topn=5)  

sim_word = []
sim_str  = []
for i in range(len(sims)):
    sim_word.append(sims[i][0])  
for i in range(len(sims)):
    sim_str.append(sims[i][1])  
sim_word = list(reversed(sim_word))
sim_str  = list(reversed(sim_str))


y = sim_word
x = sim_str
plt.style.use('ggplot')
plt.barh(y,x,color=['blue'])
plt.title('Rationalism: Similar words for happiness')

plt.xlabel('Similarity')

From the above graphs, when we feed positive word "happiness" to continental, we see wickedness is the most similar words to it. When we feed the negative word "death" to rationalism, we see the most similar words could be "father" and "mercy", words that are less negative. In some way, this also supports our claim that as time goes by, the philosophical texts has a shift in sentiment.
